<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="s_quad_resid_recipr" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Law of quadratic reciprocity</title>

    <objectives>
        <ol>
            <li>
                <p>
                    State and prove the law of quadratic reciprocity. 
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Use quadratic reciprocity to determine whether a given integer is a square modulo <m>p</m>. 
                </p>
            </li>
        </ol>
    </objectives>
    <theorem xml:id="th_quad_recip">
    <title>Law of quadratic reciprocity</title>
    <statement>
    <p>
    Let <m>p</m> and <m>q</m> be distinct odd primes. We have 
    <md number="yes">
        <mrow xml:id="eq_quad_recip">\qr{p}{q} \amp = (-1)^{\frac{p-1}{2} \cdot \frac{q-1}{2}} \qr{q}{p} </mrow>
    </md>.
    </p>
    </statement>
    </theorem>
    <p>
        Before getting to the proof of <xref ref="th_quad_recip"/>, we record a simple consequence that is often useful when computing examples. 
    </p>
    <corollary xml:id="cor_quad_recip">
        <statement>
            <p>
                Let <m>p</m> and <m>q</m> be distinct odd primes. 
                <md number="yes">
                    <mrow>\qr{p}{q} \amp = \begin{cases}
                    \qr{q}{p} \amp \text{if } p\equiv 1\pmod 4 \text{ or } q\equiv 1\pmod 4 \\
                    -\qr{q}{p} \amp \text{if } p\equiv q\equiv -1\pmod 4
                    \end{cases}</mrow>
                </md>.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </corollary>
    <proof>
        <title>Proof of quadratic reciprocity</title>
    <p>
        Consider <m>\qr{p}{q}</m>. Let 
        <md number="no">
            <mrow>R \amp = \{(kp)\boldmod q\mid 1\leq k\leq (q-1)/2\} </mrow>
            <mrow>X \amp = \{1,\dots, (q-1)/2\}</mrow>
            <mrow>Y \amp = \{(q+1)/2, \dots, q-1\}</mrow>
        </md>.
        By Gauss's lemma, letting <m>s_1,s_2,\dots, s_{n}</m> be the distinct elements of <m>R\cap Y</m> and <m>t_1,t_2,\dots, t_m</m> the distinct elements of <m>R\cap X</m>, we have <m>\qr{p}{q}=(-1)^{n}</m>. Recall also, that in our proof of <xref ref="th_gauss_lemma"/>, we showed that 
        <md>
            \{q-s_1,q-s_2,\dots, q-s_n, t_1,t_2,\dots, t_m\}=X
        </md>.
        Let's express the elements of <m>R</m> in terms of the division algorithm. For each <m>1\leq k\leq (q-1)/2</m>, we have 
        <m>(kp)\boldmod q=r_k</m>, where 
        <md>
            <mrow>kp \amp =\floor{kp/q}q+r_k</mrow>
        </md>.
        The value of <m>\qr{p}{q}=(-1)^n</m>, is determined by the parity of <m>n</m>: that is, its value modulo <m>2</m>. To assert something interesting about this, we will compute <m>\sum_{k=1}^{(p-1)/2}kp</m> in two different ways. On the one hand, we have 
        <md>
            <mrow> \amp </mrow>
        </md>
        
    </p>
    </proof>

</section>